procstep.procdesc:
The following data and datasets were assembled: 
				(1) static depth-to-water data from wells completed in the High Plains aquifer and measured after the 2012 irrigation season and before the 2013 irrigation season (Kansas Geological Survey, 2014; Texas Water Development Board, 2014; U.S. Geological Survey, 2014); 
				(2) static depth-to-water data from wells, which are located in New Mexico, completed in the High Plains aquifer, and measured after the previous year's irrigation season and before the specified year's irrigation season for 2009 to 2012 (U.S. Geological Survey, 2014); 
				(3) static depth-to-water data from wells, which are located in Wyoming, completed in the High Plains aquifer, and measured after the 2011 irrigation season and before the 2012 irrigation season (U.S. Geological Survey, 2014);
				(4) the aquifer boundary and the boundary of internal areas where the aquifer is not present (Qi, 2010); 
				(5) areas in the High Plains aquifer with little or no saturated thickness (Gutentag and others, 1984; Cederstrand and Becker, 1999a); 
				(6) the location and extent of major faults within the High Plains aquifer (Cederstrand and Becker, 1999b); 
				(7) water-level change contours, predevelopment to 2011, High Plains aquifer (McGuire, 2013); 
				(8) predevelopment and 1980 water levels for wells completed in the High Plains aquifer (Luckey and others, 1981; Gutentag and others, 1984); and 
				(9) published water-level change contours in areas with few predevelopment water levels in Wyoming and Nebraska (Lowry, 1967; Luckey and others, 1981; University of Nebraska-Lincoln, Conservation and Survey Division, 2013).

The revised raster of water-level change from predevelopment to 2013 was modified further using the Esri Arc/Info Version 10.0 commands SETNULL and CON with applicable rasters to identify the cells to be changed. The SETNULL and CON commands were applied using the following rasters 
				(1) raster g02_aqisle to change the cell values to missing data in areas where the aquifer is not present (Gutentag and others, 1984; Qi, 2010); 
				(2) rasters r1_pd13max and r2_pd13min to examine the absolute value of each cell within the polygons of water-level change to reassign the cell's value, if appropriate, to either the lower value of the corresponding range (as absolute values) for the polygon, if the cell value was less than the polygons lower value, or to the higher value of the corresponding range (as absolute values) for the polygon, if the cell value was greater than the polygons higher value; 
				(3) raster h_ldpd13_g to change the cell values to 10.01 in the areas of rises in Central Platte River Valley in Nebraska(Luckey and others, 1981; Gutentag and others, 1984); 
				(4) raster h_nscpd13_g to change the cell values to zero in the areas with water-level change between a decline of 5 ft and a rise of 5 ft, because of uncertainty in interpolating relatively small water-level changes especially in areas where there are few wells measured in both predevelopment and 2013; and 
				(5) raster gnosatpoly09 to change the cell values to missing data in the areas of little or no saturated thickness (Gutentag and others, 1984; Cederstrand and Becker, 1999a).
				The resultant raster with areas of no substantial change set to zero was titled h_ga01d_pd13. The resultant raster with areas of little or no saturated thickness set to null was titled h_ga01e_pd13.
